Principal Component Analysis

Dataset seagrass.red.scaled

This dataset contains 88 individuals and 4 variables, 1 qualitative variable is considered as illustrative.

1. Inertia distribution

The inertia of the first dimensions shows if there are strong relationships between variables and suggests the number of dimensions that should be studied.

The first two dimensions of PCA express 78.37% of the total dataset inertia ; that means that 78.37% of the individuals (or variables) cloud total variability is explained by the plane. This percentage is high and thus the first plane represents an important part of the data variability. This value is greater than the reference value that equals 78.27%, the variability explained by this plane is thus significant (the reference value is the 0.95-quantile of the inertia percentages distribution obtained by simulating 718 data tables of equivalent size on the basis of a normal distribution).

From these observations, it is probably not useful to interpret the next dimensions.

Figure 1 - Decomposition of the total inertia on the components of the PCA

An estimation of the right number of axis to interpret suggests to restrict the analysis to the description of the first 1 axis. These axis present an amount of inertia greater than those obtained by the 0.95-quantile of random distributions (46.63% against 45.48%). This observation suggests that only this axis is carrying a real information. As a consequence, the description will stand to these axis.

2. Description of the dimension 1

Figure 2.1 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction.

The Wilks test p-value indicates which variable factors are the best separated on the plane (i.e. which one explain the best the distance between individuals).

##      station 
## 4.345598e-05

There only is one possible qualitative variable to illustrate the distance between individuals : station.

Figure 2.2 - Individuals factor map (PCA) The labeled individuals are those with the higher contribution to the plane construction. The individuals are coloured after their category for the variable station.

Figure 2.3 - Variables factor map (PCA) The labeled variables are those the best shown on the plane.

Figure 2.4 - Qualitative factor map (PCA) The labeled factors are those the best shown on the plane.

The dimension 1 opposes individuals such as 40, 8, 72, 9, 27, 87, 10, 7, 84 and 86 (to the right of the graph, characterized by a strongly positive coordinate on the axis) to individuals such as 16, 19, 18, 83, NA, NA, NA, NA, NA and NA (to the left of the graph, characterized by a strongly negative coordinate on the axis).

The group in which the individuals 27, 87, 84, 86 and 26 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variable shoot_count.

The group in which the individuals 40, 8, 72, 9, 10, 7 and 41 stand (characterized by a positive coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • high values for the variables bg_biomass_wet and ag_biomass_wet (variables are sorted from the strongest).

The group in which the individuals 16, 19, 18 and 83 stand (characterized by a negative coordinate on the axis) is sharing :

  • low values for the variables ag_biomass_wet, bg_biomass_wet and shoot_count (variables are sorted from the weakest).

Note that the variable Otmanli is highly correlated with this dimension (correlation of 0.9). This variable could therefore summarize itself the dimension 1.

3. Classification

Figure 3 - Ascending Hierarchical Classification of the individuals. The classification made on individuals reveals 3 clusters.

The cluster 1 is made of individuals such as 16, 18, 19, 44 and 83. This group is characterized by :

  • low values for the variables ag_biomass_wet, shoot_count and bg_biomass_wet (variables are sorted from the weakest).

The cluster 2 is made of individuals such as 26, 27, 84, 86 and 87. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variable shoot_count.

The cluster 3 is made of individuals such as 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 40, 41 and 72. This group is characterized by :

  • high values for the variables ag_biomass_wet and bg_biomass_wet (variables are sorted from the strongest).
